metadata.name: Tezumie #1076
metadata.description:
Tezumie are interdimensional beings who seemingly spawn out of thin air. Tezumie are obsessed with Eating, fighting, and Collecting junk they find throughout the universe. Once a Token is minted, you will spawn your very own Tezumie! 

Beware, there is more to them than they let on. They are not Restricted to the blockchain, and you may notice strange things appearing and disappearing around you. You have been warned.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #342
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Napoli #59
metadata.description:
Napoli is a generative and animated piece creating an organic shape.  The position, frequency and amplitude of each lines are generated for each token, along with the color theme. Some rare items are available.

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.

At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Napoli (Italia).

metadata.name: Endless Flow #23
metadata.description:
I like to study and create flow motions which make me think of the flowing rivers, ripples in the ponds, and the heave of waves. Staring at them, watching them keep changing through time can always bring me some peace and wash my mind.
-
Features in this work including color palette, flowing speed, flow pattern and different kinds of modification.
-

metadata.name: Padina #146
metadata.description:
Padina collection focuses on the natural phenomenon where living organisms grow by adding layers of matter in a particular direction.
Formed shape resembles the algae genus Padina, but similarities can also be found in the world of fungi, like genus Trametes.

There are ten hand-picked color palettes, three composition types.
Multitude of variables control leaf surface details.
Each leaf consists of countless dots, which end up creating harmonic, or more chaotic patterns.


Double click: reset animation. 
Press "S" to save 4000px file. This can be slow.


Libs used: p5js, three.js

metadata.name: impressions 04 #63
metadata.description:
The final of four impressions, an exercise in pulling discernible patterns from utter chaos. 

Palette - One of 10 different color palettes.
Shape - Is the source an ellipse or a square?
Divisions - The X/Y resolution of the pattern.
xRand & yRand - the X and Y dimensions of each element.

metadata.name: intentions 01 #64
metadata.description:
A 3D map of an imaginary cavern is created with Perlin noise; this is sliced in to an arbitrary stack, and each slice is rendered as a dot field. This is, in turn, displayed on the screen as a rotating isometric cube. Along the bottom, one can see the total number of slices, and the gradient created by the two colors used.

Traits: 

Color 1 & Color 2: each chosen from a single pool of 10. Each color is equally likely, so the least likely result is two of the same color. 

Resolution: This is the resolution of the dot field, and describes the complexity. Three possible results, with 1 being the least likely.

Slices: The number of slices in the stack, with 5 being the least likely. 

Created in p5.js
